WEBVTT

00:01.968 --> 00:04.937
[jazz music]

00:04.971 --> 00:12.012
♪ ♪

00:18.484 --> 00:20.486
[cheers and applause]

00:20.519 --> 00:22.355
- From the Penn & Teller
Theater

00:22.388 --> 00:24.556
at the Rio Hotel in Las Vegas,

00:24.591 --> 00:28.827
here's our host
Alyson Hannigan.

00:28.861 --> 00:35.902
♪ ♪

00:39.905 --> 00:42.142
- Welcome to "Fool Us."

00:42.174 --> 00:45.578
Tonight the pressure is high
for our world-class acts

00:45.612 --> 00:47.713
who
with millions watching

00:47.746 --> 00:51.584
will try to fool two of the
most brilliant minds in magic.

00:51.618 --> 00:53.319
But you know what I say?

00:53.353 --> 00:55.454
No pressure, no diamonds.

00:55.487 --> 00:58.625
So let's bring out
our two sparkling studs,

00:58.658 --> 01:00.560
Penn and Teller!

01:00.593 --> 01:03.563
[jazz music]

01:03.596 --> 01:06.832
♪ ♪

01:06.865 --> 01:09.903
[cheers and applause]

01:14.606 --> 01:17.176
A "Fool Us" trophy will drop
from the sky

01:17.210 --> 01:20.980
and get handed to any magician
who fools Penn and Teller.

01:21.013 --> 01:24.049
Let's see if our first
performer can make it rain.

01:24.084 --> 01:26.552
[fireworks booming]

01:26.585 --> 01:29.222
- From the moment my dad
bought me my first magic book

01:29.254 --> 01:31.524
when I was 13, I was hooked.

01:31.557 --> 01:34.460
I knew then I wanted to spend
all my time

01:34.493 --> 01:37.729
and money learning magic.

01:37.764 --> 01:39.231
There's a stereotype
of magicians

01:39.265 --> 01:43.569
growing up as the awkward kid,
the odd man out.

01:43.603 --> 01:44.938
That wasn't really me.

01:44.971 --> 01:47.706
I was homecoming prince,
and my girlfriend

01:47.740 --> 01:50.777
and I won best-dressed
couple at prom.

01:50.810 --> 01:53.479
But magic did give me
a sense of purpose.

01:53.513 --> 01:55.215
And now my goal is to provide
the support

01:55.247 --> 01:57.750
and encouragement
I had for others.

01:57.783 --> 02:01.287
I can't believe I get to do
magic every night of my life.

02:01.320 --> 02:02.688
I love performing.

02:02.721 --> 02:05.024
My influences in magic
aren't even magicians.

02:05.057 --> 02:07.694
They were great entertainers
like Michael Jackson,

02:07.727 --> 02:08.694
Bruno Mars.

02:08.728 --> 02:10.697
Talk about great showmen.

02:10.729 --> 02:12.164
They've taught me
the importance

02:12.198 --> 02:14.734
of adding some personal flair
to my act.

02:14.766 --> 02:17.704
So, ladies and gentlemen,
it's showtime.

02:17.736 --> 02:22.275
[cheers and applause]

02:22.307 --> 02:25.645
- Please welcome the wonderful
Alex Ramon.

02:25.677 --> 02:27.413
[cheers and applause]

02:27.447 --> 02:29.081
- Thank you.

02:29.115 --> 02:31.584
You know, I've been
doing magic a long time.

02:31.617 --> 02:33.986
And there's a rule
when you're a magician.

02:34.020 --> 02:35.521
It's a simple rule.

02:35.555 --> 02:40.926
The rule is, you have to have
a cute blonde assistant.

02:43.163 --> 02:48.100
And this is mine.

02:48.134 --> 02:49.602
[applause]

02:49.635 --> 02:52.070
Everybody, this is MJ.

02:52.104 --> 02:55.908
MJ is a golden doxie.

02:55.942 --> 02:58.944
That's half golden retriever,
half dachshund.

02:58.978 --> 03:00.546
Don't ask me
how that happened.

03:00.580 --> 03:02.080
[laughter]

03:02.115 --> 03:06.853
This is one really brave dog.
You are now at the dog park.

03:06.885 --> 03:10.789
I named MJ
after Michael Jordan.

03:10.823 --> 03:14.593
It's just Jordan
has longer legs.

03:14.627 --> 03:21.401
Come here, boy.
Touch. Good boy. Good boy.

03:21.433 --> 03:25.371
All right.
He has some magic to show you.

03:25.405 --> 03:31.777
Let's go.
All right.

03:31.811 --> 03:35.180
Now, by now you should all
probably realize

03:35.215 --> 03:40.353
that MJ, in fact,
isn't the assistant.

03:40.385 --> 03:44.524
He's the magician.

03:44.557 --> 03:45.925
I'm the assistant.

03:45.959 --> 03:46.925
[laughter]

03:46.960 --> 03:49.996
And MJ has me well-trained.

03:55.768 --> 03:58.704
Don't you?
I forgot.

03:58.737 --> 04:01.039
He's the shorter
and silent one in the act.

04:01.074 --> 04:03.575
[laughter]

04:03.610 --> 04:05.844
Good boy.

04:05.877 --> 04:09.048
MJ gets the best dog food.

04:09.081 --> 04:10.650
Part of a balanced meal.

04:10.682 --> 04:11.717
You'll see what I mean.

04:24.564 --> 04:28.201
And I have to make sure
that everything is perfect.

04:28.233 --> 04:31.103
Otherwise,

04:31.137 --> 04:33.872
he won't do his magic.

04:36.875 --> 04:38.944
Good.

04:38.978 --> 04:45.784
Now, it's very important
to me that all of you know

04:45.817 --> 04:49.355
all of the perceived danger
during this entire illusion,

04:49.389 --> 04:53.326
the entire time,
I'm absolutely safe.

04:53.358 --> 04:54.793
[laughter]

04:54.826 --> 04:58.363
MJ is never in harm's way.

04:58.398 --> 05:00.699
He actually--he knows
how the trick works.

05:00.733 --> 05:04.937
[laughter]

05:04.971 --> 05:07.639
Okay.

05:13.312 --> 05:17.884
And now, you ready?

05:21.687 --> 05:23.389
Have you gained some weight?

05:23.423 --> 05:25.891
[laughter]

05:25.925 --> 05:27.694
Okay.

05:27.726 --> 05:31.197
This is the most difficult
part of the trick for me.

05:39.237 --> 05:42.942
And...

05:42.975 --> 05:45.711
that's my part.

05:45.745 --> 05:47.913
[cheers and applause]
Good boy, MJ.

05:47.947 --> 05:50.817
Good boy, MJ.

05:50.850 --> 05:52.317
Good boy, Alex.

05:52.351 --> 05:54.553
[laughter]

05:54.586 --> 05:56.122
Okay, now for the magic.

05:56.154 --> 05:59.257
And not even I know
how MJ does this.

06:03.730 --> 06:06.766
That's one.

06:12.105 --> 06:15.841
[audience exclaims]

06:15.875 --> 06:20.413
That's two.

06:20.446 --> 06:23.649
Good boy. Good boy.

06:23.682 --> 06:24.716
And...

06:35.161 --> 06:39.165
That is magic.

06:39.197 --> 06:41.533
[audience exclaims]

06:41.567 --> 06:43.935
[applause]

06:43.970 --> 06:47.673
Good boy. Good boy. Okay.

06:47.706 --> 06:52.011
Come on. Come.

06:52.043 --> 06:55.680
[cheers and applause]

06:55.715 --> 06:59.619
You did it.
Good boy. You did it, MJ.

06:59.651 --> 07:02.053
You did it. Good boy.

07:02.088 --> 07:04.923
- Alex Ramon and MJ.

07:04.956 --> 07:07.059
- Good boy.

07:07.093 --> 07:09.362
Hello. Hi.
- Yeah, you can see him.

07:09.394 --> 07:11.663
- Oh, hi.

07:11.697 --> 07:15.233
Oh, this is the first magician
I've wanted to make out with.

07:15.268 --> 07:16.302
- Oh.
[laughter]

07:16.334 --> 07:19.137
He'll tongue ya.
- I'm hoping for it.

07:19.172 --> 07:20.406
[laughter]

07:20.439 --> 07:24.209
So who learned magic
more quickly, you or MJ?

07:24.242 --> 07:25.812
- MJ.
[laughter]

07:25.845 --> 07:27.547
Yeah, he got better treats
than I got, though.

07:27.579 --> 07:28.848
- Oh, yeah.
- Yeah?

07:28.880 --> 07:30.283
- That's so much fun.

07:30.315 --> 07:31.817
You just get to travel
the world with your dog.

07:31.850 --> 07:34.954
- Yeah, you know what?
I had an assistant,

07:34.987 --> 07:36.555
and I needed
to get a replacement.

07:36.588 --> 07:39.425
And so I decided
I'm gonna get a dog.

07:39.459 --> 07:40.826
[laughter]

07:40.860 --> 07:42.261
He's the star of the show,
you know?

07:42.295 --> 07:43.562
- Absolutely.

07:43.596 --> 07:45.130
- He has more Instagram
followers than I have,

07:45.163 --> 07:46.531
so I mean, you know?
[laughter]

07:46.566 --> 07:49.502
- Could you imagine
not being a magician?

07:49.534 --> 07:51.603
- Honestly, I wouldn't be
doing anything else.

07:51.637 --> 07:52.704
I can't even imagine it.

07:52.737 --> 07:54.105
- Yeah.
- It's all I've ever done

07:54.139 --> 07:56.042
since I was a teenager.
I've never had another job.

07:56.074 --> 07:59.478
Just performed, and it takes me
around the world,

07:59.512 --> 08:02.214
brings me on this show,
which is amazing.

08:02.247 --> 08:03.716
- Aw.

08:03.749 --> 08:07.185
All right, Alex, let's see
if MJ fooled Penn and Teller.

08:07.220 --> 08:08.788
- Hey, Alex, boy,
what a great thing.

08:08.821 --> 08:11.790
The first thing Teller said,
I mean, just...

08:11.824 --> 08:13.492
just the second you ended was,

08:13.526 --> 08:15.427
"That's the best suspension
we've ever seen."

08:15.461 --> 08:16.528
- Thank you.

08:16.562 --> 08:17.863
- Absolutely the best
suspension.

08:17.896 --> 08:20.766
Suspensions have
real problems with them.

08:20.800 --> 08:21.901
- Yeah.

08:21.934 --> 08:23.302
- And one of the problems
is the ending.

08:23.336 --> 08:24.569
And they never have endings.

08:24.603 --> 08:26.404
You have to take it apart
slowly

08:26.439 --> 08:28.673
the way you put it
back together and pretty much

08:28.707 --> 08:31.143
just instruct the audience
on how the trick was done.

08:31.177 --> 08:34.580
And this whole thing falling
apart is a fabulous ending.

08:34.614 --> 08:36.215
And also, it has,

08:36.249 --> 08:38.683
you know--it has the dog,
which is cute.

08:38.717 --> 08:40.620
- Yeah.
- I'm not a big fan of dogs.

08:40.653 --> 08:44.557
We have one in my home, because
my children insist on it.

08:44.590 --> 08:47.360
But our relationship is
at best cordial.

08:47.393 --> 08:49.095
[laughter]

08:49.128 --> 08:50.629
- Don't listen, MJ.

08:50.663 --> 08:53.633
- But this act is--is just
great.

08:53.665 --> 08:56.034
You have the broom out there,
which makes us think

08:56.067 --> 08:59.471
broom suspension, which gets us
all set for a broom suspension.

08:59.504 --> 09:03.009
We know how that's gonna go.
And that's not the way it went.

09:03.042 --> 09:05.110
And we have--you know,

09:05.144 --> 09:07.379
there's only certain ways
you can do things.

09:07.413 --> 09:12.250
And we have a very good idea
on how you did everything,

09:12.284 --> 09:15.587
uh, except the wobble.

09:15.620 --> 09:20.058
Wobble kind of drove us crazy,
the flexibility,

09:20.091 --> 09:23.663
because suspensions
are always really rigid.

09:23.696 --> 09:25.163
- Right.

09:25.197 --> 09:26.499
- They have to be really rigid
because of the way it works,

09:26.532 --> 09:29.936
and you had
this flexibility in there.

09:29.969 --> 09:32.171
And you're a lovely couple,
but now it's time

09:32.203 --> 09:33.438
to play the game,

09:33.471 --> 09:34.941
'cause you know
we know everything else.

09:34.974 --> 09:36.908
- Mm-hmm.
- There is no surprise there.

09:36.942 --> 09:39.544
And in order to not be fooled,
we had to

09:39.578 --> 09:42.514
figure out that wobble.
And I gotta tell you,

09:42.548 --> 09:48.754
you--you do not get a trophy
this time, Alex,

09:48.788 --> 09:51.456
because MJ gets the trophy.

09:51.490 --> 09:53.024
- [gasps]
- 'Cause we couldn't figure out

09:53.058 --> 09:54.159
what that was
for the life of us.

09:54.192 --> 09:55.794
- Oh, my God.
MJ, you did it, boy.

09:55.827 --> 09:57.363
You did it.
- Not for the life of us.

09:57.395 --> 09:58.965
We could not figure out
that wobble.

09:58.998 --> 10:01.167
- Boy, you did it.
Boy, you did it.

10:01.200 --> 10:02.467
- You did a good job.

10:02.500 --> 10:04.070
And you can show affection
with the dog.

10:04.102 --> 10:05.870
I'll stay over here
with Alyson.

10:05.904 --> 10:07.373
- Good boy.
Good boy, you did it.

10:07.405 --> 10:09.674
Thank you, guys, so much.
- Congratulations.

10:09.708 --> 10:13.678
- Thank you.
- MJ and Alex Ramon.

10:13.712 --> 10:17.549
- You did it, boy! You did it.

10:17.582 --> 10:19.652
- You've just seen the first
ever "Fool Us"

10:19.684 --> 10:22.053
trophy won by a dog.

10:22.087 --> 10:25.557
Who knows what else will happen
when "Fool Us" returns.

10:25.591 --> 10:28.561
[jazz music]

10:28.594 --> 10:30.162
♪ ♪

10:33.466 --> 10:36.434
[jazz music]

10:36.469 --> 10:38.004
♪ ♪

10:38.037 --> 10:39.471
- Welcome back.

10:39.504 --> 10:42.908
If you're just joining us,
you missed one fooler already.

10:42.942 --> 10:45.043
Don't worry; there may be more.

10:45.076 --> 10:47.812
Let's meet our next
possible fooler.

10:47.846 --> 10:50.282
[fireworks booming]

10:50.316 --> 10:53.318
- Every magician's dream
is to levitate for real.

10:53.351 --> 10:56.655
So I learned to fly
and do magic at the same time.

10:56.688 --> 11:00.125
I've done mentalism
floating in a wind tunnel.

11:00.158 --> 11:01.894
And I can juggle
and do backflips

11:01.927 --> 11:04.996
blindfolded on a trampoline.

11:05.030 --> 11:07.332
Suspending gravity
while I perform,

11:07.365 --> 11:09.769
it means some of the miracle
happens to me.

11:09.802 --> 11:12.804
It connects me to the wow
I felt the first time

11:12.837 --> 11:14.373
I ever saw a magic trick.

11:14.407 --> 11:17.342
That feeling of amazement is
something I'm always chasing.

11:17.375 --> 11:20.046
That's why a lot of my tricks
use a volunteer

11:20.078 --> 11:22.347
in what I think
is a unique way.

11:22.380 --> 11:25.384
They're the magician.
I witness the magic.

11:25.418 --> 11:28.386
But the magic
comes from them, not me.

11:28.421 --> 11:30.956
The other thing I like to do
is to tell a story

11:30.990 --> 11:35.695
with a beginning,
a middle, and an end.

11:35.727 --> 11:37.830
I'm a big Edgar Allan Poe fan,
for example.

11:37.863 --> 11:41.433
And I produce a variety magic
show in his honor every year.

11:41.466 --> 11:44.636
Storytelling is what I hope
to do on "Fool Us" too.

11:44.669 --> 11:47.273
The ending of that story,
it's up to Penn and Teller

11:47.306 --> 11:50.308
and maybe just
a little bit up to me.

11:50.341 --> 11:54.145
[cheers and applause]

11:54.179 --> 11:57.149
- Give it up
for the magic of Micah.

11:57.182 --> 11:58.149
[cheers and applause]

11:58.183 --> 11:59.518
- Thank you.

11:59.552 --> 12:01.620
Thank you so much.
It's such an honor to be here.

12:01.653 --> 12:05.924
And as much as I would love to
perform the most mind-blowing,

12:05.957 --> 12:09.095
ass-kicking trick
you've ever seen.

12:09.128 --> 12:11.730
I think Alyson should do it.
Guys, give it up for Alyson.

12:11.764 --> 12:13.198
Alyson, will you join me?
[applause]

12:13.231 --> 12:15.868
Will you step into my office,
please? Yeah.

12:15.900 --> 12:17.102
- This could be a mistake.

12:17.135 --> 12:19.804
[laughter]
- No, no. I love mistakes. Yes.

12:19.838 --> 12:22.707
Alyson, it's such an honor.
Thank you for being here.

12:22.741 --> 12:24.643
Are you ready
to possibly perform

12:24.677 --> 12:27.513
the most kickass trick
ever on this stage?

12:27.546 --> 12:29.014
- Sure.
- Okay, fantastic.

12:29.048 --> 12:30.548
So, Alyson, for this to work,

12:30.582 --> 12:33.384
I want you to be as still
and relaxed as possible.

12:33.418 --> 12:35.520
- Oh!
[laughter]

12:35.553 --> 12:37.155
- So, Alyson, as you know,

12:37.188 --> 12:39.091
all the cards are separated
into two groups.

12:39.125 --> 12:42.827
Okay? They are all either black
or they are red.

12:42.861 --> 12:43.962
Alyson, makes sense to you?

12:43.995 --> 12:45.264
- Yes.
- Cool.

12:45.297 --> 12:46.999
Makes sense to you guys?
Pretty simple. Here we go.

12:47.032 --> 12:49.735
Oh, Alyson, will you mix up
the cards, please?

12:49.769 --> 12:52.504
Yeah, just give it a quick--I
want to see the Alyson shuffle.

12:52.538 --> 12:53.972
- Oh-oh.
[laughter]

12:54.005 --> 12:55.274
- I have nothing
but faith in you.

12:55.307 --> 12:58.476
Yes, the Alyson shuffle.
I've seen this on YouTube.

12:58.510 --> 12:59.778
But--oh, but never in person.

12:59.812 --> 13:01.846
This is very exciting.
Alyson, I love it.

13:01.880 --> 13:03.615
I love your style.
You're doing great.

13:03.649 --> 13:05.017
Yeah, and you can stop
at any time.

13:05.049 --> 13:07.318
You're doing great.
The Alyson shuffle.

13:07.352 --> 13:09.355
Give it up for the Alyson
shuffle. That was wonderful.

13:09.388 --> 13:11.490
All right, so here we go.
Here we go. Are you ready?

13:11.524 --> 13:15.961
All right, here we go.
Black or red, Alyson?

13:15.995 --> 13:17.897
- Black.
- Nice.

13:17.929 --> 13:18.898
- Yeah, look at this,
pretty good.

13:18.931 --> 13:20.099
Now, she had a 50-50 shot.

13:20.131 --> 13:21.667
We would expect
that kind of luck.

13:21.700 --> 13:22.768
But, Alyson,
that was very good.

13:22.802 --> 13:24.068
That's was very good.
Here we go.

13:24.102 --> 13:27.539
Next card.
Black or red?

13:27.572 --> 13:29.975
- Red.
[applause]

13:30.009 --> 13:31.243
- Have you ever done
this before?

13:31.277 --> 13:32.845
- No.
- This is amazing.

13:32.878 --> 13:34.580
Now twice in a row. I mean,
that could have been lucky.

13:34.613 --> 13:38.116
But still that's very good.
Here we go. Black or red?

13:38.149 --> 13:41.787
Alyson?
- Red.

13:41.821 --> 13:43.188
[applause]

13:43.221 --> 13:44.657
- Alyson, this is incredible.
Now, here's the thing.

13:44.690 --> 13:46.024
Alyson, did you have any idea

13:46.057 --> 13:47.293
you were gonna be
a part of this?

13:47.326 --> 13:48.427
- No.
- No, no, no.

13:48.460 --> 13:49.828
And that's part
of the rules, right?

13:49.861 --> 13:51.397
You can't--this isn't a setup.
But what would happen

13:51.429 --> 13:53.298
if I remove myself
from the equation?

13:53.331 --> 13:58.070
Alyson, next card,
black or red?

13:58.102 --> 13:59.804
- Oh.
- Just call it.

13:59.838 --> 14:01.173
- Black.
- Yes.

14:01.206 --> 14:03.008
And I love your instincts.
Will you do the honors?

14:03.042 --> 14:04.876
I don't want to touch it.
What did you say, black?

14:04.909 --> 14:05.878
- Oh.

14:05.910 --> 14:07.078
- Oh, okay.
[applause]

14:07.111 --> 14:08.147
All right, Alyson,
let's do another one.

14:08.179 --> 14:11.082
Black or red? Alyson?

14:11.115 --> 14:12.518
- Red.

14:12.551 --> 14:14.620
- There's only one way
to find out.

14:14.653 --> 14:16.054
Get out! This is incredible.
[applause]

14:16.087 --> 14:19.057
- Okay, Alyson, black or red?

14:19.091 --> 14:20.525
- Red.
- I'm freaking out too.

14:20.558 --> 14:22.727
[laughter]
You are doing amazing.

14:22.760 --> 14:25.397
Will you do the honors?
What do we got?

14:25.431 --> 14:27.265
- Oh!
- This is incredible! Okay.

14:27.298 --> 14:29.235
Black or red, Alyson?

14:29.268 --> 14:34.840
- Red.
- Okay. You said red. Yeah?

14:34.874 --> 14:36.808
- I don't...
[applause]

14:36.841 --> 14:39.544
Okay, Alyson.
You've never done this before?

14:39.577 --> 14:40.946
- No.

14:40.980 --> 14:42.147
- This might be one of
the greatest mentalism things

14:42.181 --> 14:44.015
ever,
and you're the one doing it.

14:44.048 --> 14:47.485
I'm merely a vessel.
Alyson, here's the thing.

14:47.519 --> 14:50.556
Why would you stop
at the color?

14:50.588 --> 14:54.793
Right? Suspense, Alyson.

14:54.826 --> 14:58.197
Suspense, suspense.
Black or red, Alyson?

14:58.230 --> 14:59.631
- Red.
- Red?

14:59.664 --> 15:04.602
- Yeah.
- Okay. Diamonds or hearts?

15:04.636 --> 15:06.171
- Diamonds.
- Okay?

15:06.205 --> 15:10.042
I like how you said diamonds.
It was almost evil. I love it.

15:10.075 --> 15:13.846
Okay, diamond. Number diamond
or letter diamond?

15:13.879 --> 15:15.547
- You know, number being
self-explanatory. Letter--

15:15.581 --> 15:17.950
yeah, you're an old hat
at this. Yeah.

15:17.982 --> 15:19.217
- Number.
- Number. Okay.

15:19.250 --> 15:22.120
Low number diamond
or high number diamond?

15:22.153 --> 15:23.187
- Low.

15:23.221 --> 15:24.657
- Low number diamond?
- Yeah.

15:24.690 --> 15:27.860
- That'll make this a two
diamonds, a three of diamonds,

15:27.893 --> 15:30.395
a four of diamonds,
a five of diamonds.

15:30.428 --> 15:32.298
I'll even throw in a six.

15:32.331 --> 15:34.667
- Two.
- Two of diamonds?

15:34.700 --> 15:37.735
Honestly, you claim
you've never done this before.

15:37.769 --> 15:41.539
That's your claim. Yeah?
Okay, here's--here's the thing.

15:41.572 --> 15:42.607
What was that the two
of diamonds?

15:42.640 --> 15:44.543
I put myself back
into the equation,

15:44.576 --> 15:46.010
I reintroduced the old problem.

15:46.044 --> 15:49.347
What would happen if Alyson
were completely on her own?

15:49.380 --> 15:51.716
Alyson, do you want
to mix up the cards any more?

15:51.750 --> 15:52.750
- Sure.

15:52.784 --> 15:54.052
- Yeah, I don't
trust you either.

15:54.086 --> 15:55.053
You're freaking me out.
This--yeah.

15:55.086 --> 15:56.721
- Let me just mix these.

15:56.754 --> 15:59.357
- Oh, oh. Okay.

15:59.390 --> 16:02.027
There's nothing disturbing
about any of this.

16:02.061 --> 16:03.928
[laughter]
You're doing great.

16:03.962 --> 16:05.931
Okay. Oh,
but you're very thorough.

16:05.965 --> 16:09.301
They always--they told me
that about you. Okay.

16:09.335 --> 16:10.702
- Did they?
- Yes, they did. Okay.

16:10.735 --> 16:15.640
So are you satisfied
they're mixed?

16:15.673 --> 16:17.442
The Alyson one-card burn,

16:17.475 --> 16:21.346
signature move,
you know, right?

16:21.379 --> 16:24.249
Alyson, Alyson,
will you spread out the cards?

16:24.283 --> 16:26.451
Yeah.
And will you touch any card?

16:26.485 --> 16:29.087
Yeah. Okay, get handsy.
That's cool.

16:29.120 --> 16:31.423
It's the finale? Why not?
Touch any card you wish.

16:31.456 --> 16:33.225
- Mmm. This one.

16:33.258 --> 16:34.326
- Do you want to change
your mind?

16:34.360 --> 16:35.727
- Sure.
- Yeah, I don't trust you.

16:35.760 --> 16:36.794
- That one.
- Okay.

16:36.828 --> 16:37.796
Do you want
to change your mind?

16:37.830 --> 16:38.998
- No.
- Keep it facedown,

16:39.030 --> 16:39.999
so we slide it to the side,
separate it

16:40.032 --> 16:43.235
from the rest of the deck.

16:43.268 --> 16:46.071
Okay, Alyson,
this is the one that you like?

16:46.105 --> 16:50.775
Okay, here we go.
Black or red?

16:50.808 --> 16:54.645
- Red.
- Red? Okay. Okay. Red.

16:54.679 --> 16:57.915
Is it hearts or is it diamonds?
- Hearts.

16:57.950 --> 17:02.254
- Is it--is it a number card
or a letter card?

17:02.287 --> 17:03.288
- Letter.
- Letter?

17:03.322 --> 17:04.890
Okay, yeah. That's cool.

17:04.923 --> 17:09.595
Letter card. That would
make this a jack of hearts,

17:09.627 --> 17:16.268
a queen of hearts,
a king of hearts, or an ace?

17:16.300 --> 17:18.202
- I'll go queen.
- You'll go queen? Oh, oh.

17:18.237 --> 17:19.438
- I'll go queen.

17:19.471 --> 17:22.473
- Okay. Okay, did you look
at this card?

17:22.508 --> 17:24.009
- Underneath? No. No.

17:24.042 --> 17:25.076
- Exactly.
Did you show it to me?

17:25.109 --> 17:26.244
- No.
- Did you show it to them?

17:26.278 --> 17:27.846
- No.
- If this is the queen

17:27.880 --> 17:30.982
of hearts you've done
the most amazing thing ever.

17:31.016 --> 17:33.451
No one's looked at this card
from a deck that you shuffled.

17:33.484 --> 17:34.920
But only if it's
the queen of hearts.

17:34.952 --> 17:37.388
Alyson, will you do the honors?

17:37.423 --> 17:40.325
And I'm nervous.
Will you show us first?

17:40.358 --> 17:45.029
- Show us first?
- Yeah, yeah.

17:45.064 --> 17:47.266
Alyson, I don't know, you--

17:47.298 --> 17:48.366
[cheers and applause]

17:48.400 --> 17:51.103
- Micah, everyone!
[applause]

17:51.135 --> 17:52.604
Oh, my goodness.

17:52.637 --> 17:53.771
- You were incredible.

17:53.806 --> 17:57.375
- Oh. That was ridiculous.

17:57.409 --> 18:00.945
- Alyson, how long have
you been a magician?

18:00.979 --> 18:04.348
- Wait, we've reversed.
Are you trying to get my job?

18:04.383 --> 18:05.784
- I think you're trying
to get my job.

18:05.817 --> 18:07.286
[laughter]
- What would you say

18:07.318 --> 18:09.654
the number one talent
a magician needs?

18:09.688 --> 18:12.124
- I think going
with your feelings,

18:12.156 --> 18:14.125
going with your gut,
and trusting yourself.

18:14.159 --> 18:15.661
That's what you did tonight.

18:15.693 --> 18:19.597
- So what do you mean when you
say everyone has magic inside?

18:19.631 --> 18:20.898
- I think you just proved it.

18:20.932 --> 18:23.000
Everyone can do things
that they never thought

18:23.035 --> 18:25.037
they could do.
You had no idea

18:25.069 --> 18:27.405
you were gonna do this
at all until that moment.

18:27.439 --> 18:28.473
- Yeah.

18:28.507 --> 18:30.174
- And you knocked it
out of the park.

18:30.209 --> 18:31.910
- Why, thank you.
- Well, thank you.

18:31.943 --> 18:34.645
I can't guarantee everyone
will be as good as you.

18:34.680 --> 18:37.615
But it is proof that people
can make magic happen

18:37.648 --> 18:39.785
without even knowing
how they're doing it.

18:39.817 --> 18:42.753
And to me that is real magic.
- All right, Micah.

18:42.788 --> 18:44.655
Let's see if the boys
figured out your trick.

18:44.690 --> 18:46.491
- Fair enough.

18:46.525 --> 18:47.492
- Hey, Micah.
- Yeah.

18:47.526 --> 18:48.894
- What a great, great routine.

18:48.926 --> 18:50.061
- Thank you so much.

18:50.095 --> 18:52.597
- I mean, no hoo-ha,
no counting cards,

18:52.631 --> 18:56.801
no stacking, no false shuffles,
none of that jive.

18:56.835 --> 18:59.270
Just you want to see a miracle,
we got one for you.

18:59.304 --> 19:00.372
- Thank you.

19:00.404 --> 19:01.740
- And it was really,
really beautiful.

19:01.772 --> 19:03.241
We've seen tricks like this,

19:03.275 --> 19:06.278
but this is really a marked
improvement on a lot of them.

19:06.310 --> 19:08.212
Really, really nice
and beautiful.

19:08.247 --> 19:11.083
But, you know,
when I see something like this,

19:11.115 --> 19:13.152
it really makes me laugh and
you're a really funny person.

19:13.184 --> 19:16.555
- Thank you.
- I go back to--to my heroes

19:16.587 --> 19:19.023
of comedy who are known

19:19.057 --> 19:20.959
as Horwitz, Horwitz,
and Feinstein.

19:20.992 --> 19:22.059
You know who
I'm talking about?

19:22.094 --> 19:23.628
- I think I do.
- Now, Micah,

19:23.662 --> 19:26.565
I see you smiling right away,
'cause you're an aficionado.

19:26.597 --> 19:28.467
But for those who don't know
all about it,

19:28.500 --> 19:30.602
I'm talking about
The Three Stooges,

19:30.635 --> 19:33.672
Moe, Larry, and Curly.
And actually it was Shemp,

19:33.704 --> 19:35.406
and then he was replaced
by Curly,

19:35.440 --> 19:37.009
and that's when
the act changed.

19:37.041 --> 19:38.710
When Babe Horwitz came in,

19:38.743 --> 19:41.246
Curly Howard, they went
from tapping each other

19:41.279 --> 19:43.080
to really smacking each other.
[laughter]

19:43.115 --> 19:45.416
They--oh, yeah, they went from
tapping to smacking.

19:45.450 --> 19:46.852
- It's true.

19:46.884 --> 19:49.387
- And that's when "The
Three Stooges" really took off.

19:49.421 --> 19:50.689
- Yes.
- I gotta tell you,

19:50.721 --> 19:52.156
it was really, really great.

19:52.191 --> 19:54.926
No jive, just went there
and killed

19:54.960 --> 19:57.596
and blew Alyson's mind,
blew our mind.

19:57.628 --> 20:01.666
But I think maybe we have
a pretty good idea,

20:01.700 --> 20:04.936
and I think I snuck it to you
in some of the Feinstein there.

20:04.970 --> 20:06.438
What do you think?

20:06.471 --> 20:08.941
- So, Micah, do they know
how you made me a magician?

20:08.973 --> 20:11.210
- Yeah. I think they do.
But it was such a pleasure.

20:11.242 --> 20:12.310
Thank you, guys.
- Aw.

20:12.344 --> 20:13.311
- Thank you, Micah.
It was great.

20:13.345 --> 20:14.413
- Thank you so much.

20:14.445 --> 20:16.048
- Thank you so much.
Thank you, guys.

20:16.080 --> 20:19.384
- Micah!
[cheers and applause]

20:19.417 --> 20:21.720
We've got more amazing magic
for you,

20:21.752 --> 20:24.088
including tonight's finale,

20:24.122 --> 20:26.924
a trick by Penn
and Teller themselves.

20:26.959 --> 20:28.093
Stick around.

20:28.125 --> 20:31.096
[jazz music]

20:31.128 --> 20:32.698
♪ ♪

20:36.000 --> 20:38.971
[jazz music]

20:39.003 --> 20:40.939
♪ ♪

20:40.972 --> 20:42.607
- Welcome back to "Fool Us."

20:42.641 --> 20:45.076
It's time to release
our next magician.

20:45.109 --> 20:47.278
[fireworks booming]

20:47.311 --> 20:49.615
- Hi.
My name is Cameron Young.

20:49.647 --> 20:50.915
And I've been
a close-up magician

20:50.949 --> 20:52.384
for the past ten years.

20:52.416 --> 20:54.619
And I'm based in Scotland.

20:54.653 --> 20:56.488
I've been lucky enough
to travel the world

20:56.520 --> 20:58.890
studying the art
of close-up magic,

20:58.923 --> 21:01.792
stunts,
and dangerous routines.

21:01.826 --> 21:03.929
And I was lucky enough to win
the Edinburgh Close-up

21:03.961 --> 21:07.164
Magician of the Year
every year since 2018.

21:07.199 --> 21:09.934
Penn and Teller
may also recognize me,

21:09.968 --> 21:14.205
because I also became
Penn's daughter's magic coach.

21:14.239 --> 21:17.541
Yes.
I used to teach Moxie Jillette.

21:17.576 --> 21:19.978
Since then,
I have my very own daughter.

21:20.011 --> 21:22.146
Her name is Phoebe Young.
So tonight

21:22.180 --> 21:24.348
I'd like to dedicate
my performance to Phoebe.

21:24.383 --> 21:27.118
I hope I make you proud.
Penn and Teller,

21:27.152 --> 21:30.021
tonight from Scotland
I'd like to share with you

21:30.055 --> 21:32.958
something I've been working on
for many years.

21:32.990 --> 21:35.727
I want to show you
what I can do.

21:35.760 --> 21:39.897
Hopefully, I can fool you.

21:39.931 --> 21:42.534
[cheers and applause]

21:42.567 --> 21:47.239
- All the way from the U.K.,
give it up for Cameron Young.

21:47.271 --> 21:49.340
[cheers and applause]

21:49.374 --> 21:52.076
- Hey, guys. Hey, Penn.
Hey, Teller. Hey, Alyson.

21:52.109 --> 21:53.077
- Hey! Wow.

21:53.111 --> 21:56.181
- When I was 14 years old

21:56.213 --> 21:58.950
I watched "Penn & Teller:
Fool Us" for the first time.

21:58.983 --> 22:02.287
And at that moment,
I fell in love with magic.

22:02.320 --> 22:04.256
There was three things
I realized.

22:04.288 --> 22:07.092
One, how much I loved magic.

22:07.125 --> 22:11.063
Two, how amazing it would be
to be in a double act.

22:11.096 --> 22:13.498
And three, I loved it

22:13.531 --> 22:16.468
when a magician
would do a dangerous stunt.

22:16.500 --> 22:21.373
So in my hand I have
these four pieces of string.

22:21.405 --> 22:26.345
And not only that,
this fishing hook.

22:26.377 --> 22:31.549
Tonight another one of my
dreams is about to come true,

22:31.583 --> 22:36.922
because it's time for you
to meet my double act partner.

22:36.954 --> 22:38.723
- Oh.

22:38.757 --> 22:42.661
- Yes, I have my very own
double act partner.

22:42.693 --> 22:48.165
The reason why I need a partner
is because I have four strings

22:48.200 --> 22:53.137
and a fishing hook in my mouth.

22:53.171 --> 22:55.374
Each of you are going
to command me

22:55.406 --> 22:59.211
to pull a piece of this string.

22:59.243 --> 23:02.847
I have colored
each of the strings red,

23:02.881 --> 23:05.817
blue, green, and white.

23:05.851 --> 23:09.921
Just think of it
as a dangerous game of fishing,

23:09.954 --> 23:15.394
where you could catch
a largemouth me.

23:15.426 --> 23:18.663
[laughter]
Penn, let's start with you.

23:18.696 --> 23:19.865
- Red, please.

23:19.897 --> 23:23.501
- And on the count of three,
I will pull.

23:23.535 --> 23:29.974
Three, two, one.

23:30.008 --> 23:33.211
Are you okay up there,
Cameron?

23:33.244 --> 23:34.346
[laughter]

23:34.378 --> 23:35.646
Perfect.

23:35.680 --> 23:39.284
It looked like
that went to plan.

23:39.317 --> 23:43.020
Teller, now it's your turn.

23:43.054 --> 23:44.556
On my go,

23:44.588 --> 23:48.894
I will need you to whisper
to Penn one of the colors.

23:48.926 --> 23:55.700
And then I will get Penn
to name that color out loud.

23:55.733 --> 23:59.104
On you go, Teller.

23:59.136 --> 24:04.643
- Oh. White, white.
- Perfect.

24:04.675 --> 24:07.913
- And again, on the count
of three,

24:07.945 --> 24:10.848
I am going to pull that string.

24:10.882 --> 24:12.683
- Bleh.

24:12.717 --> 24:18.589
- Three, two, one.

24:18.623 --> 24:20.090
[audience gasps]

24:20.125 --> 24:26.798
Cameron, are you sure
you still want to go on?

24:26.832 --> 24:30.669
Alyson, I'm sorry,
but I have to do this to you.

24:30.701 --> 24:34.072
There is two pieces
of string left.

24:34.105 --> 24:38.042
One is attached
to the fishing hook.

24:38.076 --> 24:41.712
If you name the wrong string,

24:41.746 --> 24:44.816
this will end badly...

24:44.849 --> 24:47.652
- Why did I have to do that?
- And this could permanently

24:47.685 --> 24:50.654
mangle my tongue.

24:50.689 --> 24:57.662
Alyson, remember, you do not
get to change your mind.

24:57.695 --> 25:02.233
Now,
please name your color.

25:02.267 --> 25:05.135
- Ehh...blue.

25:05.170 --> 25:07.137
- For the final time.

25:07.172 --> 25:11.609
Three, two, one.

25:14.246 --> 25:18.282
And tied to the final string
is the dangerous fishing hook.

25:18.316 --> 25:20.285
Alyson, Penn,

25:20.317 --> 25:24.722
Teller, that is what you call
a successful fishing trip.

25:24.756 --> 25:26.991
[cheers and applause]

25:27.025 --> 25:30.895
- Ladies and gentlemen,
Cameron Young!

25:30.929 --> 25:34.598
Oh. Cameron,
why did I have to go last?

25:34.633 --> 25:36.902
- Wow, I'm just glad you chose
the right one.

25:36.934 --> 25:38.036
I'm so glad
you choose the right one.

25:38.068 --> 25:39.336
- Me too.

25:39.371 --> 25:42.773
Oh, and what other
dangerous tricks do you do?

25:42.807 --> 25:46.443
- I have put a nail
through my hand.

25:46.478 --> 25:49.047
I also do a thing
with a massive animal trap.

25:49.079 --> 25:50.848
- And your parents are okay
with this?

25:50.882 --> 25:53.351
- My parents were so proud
when I got into magic.

25:53.384 --> 25:54.752
My parents were so proud.

25:54.786 --> 25:58.589
- Are they still?
Have they seen this trick?

25:58.623 --> 25:59.924
- They've seen it go wrong.

25:59.958 --> 26:02.259
- Oh, dear. That's not good.

26:02.294 --> 26:04.261
- The first time they
watched me perform this

26:04.296 --> 26:05.864
it went through my tongue.

26:05.896 --> 26:07.231
[audience exclaims]
- Oh.

26:07.265 --> 26:08.967
- To be honest, when I was
at school growing up,

26:09.000 --> 26:12.136
I was completely different.
I didn't fit in. Every weekend,

26:12.170 --> 26:14.271
I would be watching
"Penn & Teller: Fool Us."

26:14.306 --> 26:16.708
And I realized, "You know
what? This is for me.

26:16.740 --> 26:19.411
"I'm going to be a magician,
a stunt artist.

26:19.443 --> 26:21.645
And I want to travel
the world doing what I do."

26:21.680 --> 26:22.980
And so far, so good.

26:23.013 --> 26:26.284
- So when you found magic,
you found your people?

26:26.317 --> 26:27.618
- It's the best thing
that's ever happened to me.

26:27.652 --> 26:28.720
If it wasn't for magic,

26:28.752 --> 26:30.288
who knows
what I'd be doing now.

26:30.321 --> 26:33.557
- Okay, Cameron, let's see
if the boys can unravel

26:33.592 --> 26:37.429
the method to your magic.
Boys.

26:37.461 --> 26:39.864
- Hey, Cameron, how you doing?

26:39.897 --> 26:41.432
- I'm good, Penn. How are you?

26:41.465 --> 26:44.469
- Very well. Moxie is gonna be
so thrilled you're on the show.

26:44.501 --> 26:47.838
You were my daughter's magic
teacher at camp.

26:47.872 --> 26:50.709
You came out, worked with her
on stuff. She did shows.

26:50.741 --> 26:54.045
And she loved
being taught magic by you.

26:54.078 --> 26:56.114
She prefers being taught magic

26:56.146 --> 26:59.851
by you than being taught magic
by me or by Teller.

26:59.884 --> 27:02.019
- I will take that.
I will take that any day.

27:02.053 --> 27:05.089
- You were--you were her idol.
But let's get this straight.

27:05.123 --> 27:10.194
And now you come on my show
after teaching my daughter

27:10.228 --> 27:12.196
and think you can fool me?

27:12.230 --> 27:14.499
Yo, yo, I don't think so.
[laughter]

27:14.531 --> 27:16.768
I do want to say, first of all,

27:16.800 --> 27:20.204
great job
at making Alyson squeamish

27:20.238 --> 27:24.009
from 8,000 miles away.
That seems impossible.

27:24.041 --> 27:26.510
And the double screen thing
was really great.

27:26.544 --> 27:27.912
And I'll also tell you

27:27.945 --> 27:31.249
that we are working magicians
in Las Vegas.

27:31.281 --> 27:35.452
People come to us with tricks.
Unfortunately for you,

27:35.487 --> 27:39.423
someone came to us
with this trick and said,

27:39.457 --> 27:43.260
"Do you guys want to do this?"
So they explained it all to us.

27:43.294 --> 27:47.598
So from the moment we saw that
you didn't have a chance,

27:47.632 --> 27:51.836
because this is a trick that we
had considered doing ourselves.

27:51.869 --> 27:54.372
But you did a great,
great job with it.

27:54.405 --> 27:59.044
And I cannot wait to tell Moxie
that you were on the show.

27:59.076 --> 28:02.247
She'll be out of her mind.
She's going back to that camp.

28:02.279 --> 28:05.450
And I don't think she'll have
a teacher as good as you.

28:05.482 --> 28:06.451
- Aw!

28:06.483 --> 28:07.818
- Oh, thank you
very much, Penn.

28:07.852 --> 28:09.354
Thanks, Teller. It's been
an honor to be on your show.

28:09.386 --> 28:11.388
- So nice to have you on,
Cameron. Thanks so much.

28:11.423 --> 28:14.259
- Aw, thank you. Cameron Young!

28:14.291 --> 28:16.394
[cheers and applause]

28:22.400 --> 28:24.702
We'll let you reset your brain
for a minute,

28:24.736 --> 28:28.573
but there's more mind-blowing
magic right after the break.

